Liberalism
pasted-image.tiff
Liberalism has had three main strands of thought, but what unites these strands is the belief that “cooperation [i]s more pervasive than even the defensive version of realism allow[s].”
Each strand focuses on a different method or means of promoting it.
The first insists that countries would be less likely to get into conflict if they share economic goals.
The second postulates that the spread of democracy can potentially end world conflict, arguing that democratic states are innately more peaceful than authoritarian ones.

Third, some liberal theorists argue that major international bodies like the International Energy Agency (IEA) and International Monetary Fund (IMF) could encourage states to work together and thus avoid conflict.
